{# /views/docs/themes.twig #}
{% extends "@core/docs/_layout.twig" %}

{% block doc_content %}
    <div class="space-y-8 max-w-4xl mx-auto py-4">
        
        <header class="space-y-2">
            <h1 class="text-3xl font-black text-white tracking-tight">Theme Customization &amp; Architecture</h1>
            <p class="text-slate-400 text-lg">
                Discover how to seamlessly customize layouts, preserve core system updates, or implement entirely custom design systems using Rhapsody's extensible layout inheritance architecture.
            </p>
        </header>

        <hr class="border-slate-800">

        <section class="space-y-4">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white tracking-tight flex items-center gap-2">
                The Golden Rule: Inheritance vs. Overriding
            </h2>
            <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
                Historically, customizing web application layouts meant copy-pasting the framework's main layout file directly into a custom folder and modifying it. 
                <strong class="text-rose-400 font-semibold">This approach is a critical anti-pattern.</strong> When you duplicate the entire main layout file, your custom theme forks away from the core codebase. If a future framework update introduces a mandatory security wrapper, critical metadata structures, or new diagnostic UI features, your layout remains blind to them, breaking layout consistency or core functionality during an update.
            </p>
            <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
                Instead, Rhapsody leverages <strong class="text-indigo-400">Twig Template Inheritance</strong> and a fallback cascade pathing mechanism. By establishing protected, granular blocks inside the base architecture, you can target, append to, or rewrite individual elements (like page titles, unique body styles, scripts, or stylesheets) while ensuring that baseline layouts, analytic payloads, and functional framework states remain updated globally.
            </p>
        </section>

        <hr class="border-slate-800">

        <section class="space-y-4">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white tracking-tight">The Theme Filesystem Cascade</h2>
            <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
                The framework uses a cascading loader array configured via the dependency injection container. When your controllers request a view template file path, the engine dynamically looks up files according to the following strict inheritance hierarchy:
            </p>
            
            <div class="bg-slate-950 border border-slate-800 rounded-xl p-5 space-y-3 font-mono text-xs">
                <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
                    <span class="bg-emerald-500/10 text-emerald-400 px-2 py-0.5 rounded font-bold uppercase tracking-wider">Priority 1</span>
                    <div>
                        <span class="text-slate-200 block font-semibold text-sm">Application Theme Workspace Override</span>
                        <span class="text-slate-500">my-awesome-app/views/themes/{active_theme}/...</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="border-t border-slate-900 my-2"></div>
                <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
                    <span class="bg-indigo-500/10 text-indigo-400 px-2 py-0.5 rounded font-bold uppercase tracking-wider">Priority 2</span>
                    <div>
                        <span class="text-slate-200 block font-semibold text-sm">Application Root Views</span>
                        <span class="text-slate-500">my-awesome-app/views/...</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="border-t border-slate-900 my-2"></div>
                <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
                    <span class="bg-amber-500/10 text-amber-400 px-2 py-0.5 rounded font-bold uppercase tracking-wider">Priority 3</span>
                    <div>
                        <span class="text-slate-200 block font-semibold text-sm">Core Core Vendor Fallback</span>
                        <span class="text-slate-500">vendor/arout/rhapsody-core/resources/views/themes/default/...</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
                This behavior enables you to design brand new views within your workspace layout folders or copy individual components to your local application structure to act as an instantaneous override. If a file is omitted in the downstream workspace application layout, the framework smoothly defaults back to its vendor counterpart.
            </p>
        </section>

        <hr class="border-slate-800">

        <section class="space-y-4">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white tracking-tight">Core Layout Architecture (<code>main.twig</code>)</h2>
            <p class="text-slate-300">
                The standard structural shell is located at <code>@core/layouts/main.twig</code>. It isolates the underlying document into distinct, targetable structural blocks:
            </p>
            
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-slate-300 pl-4 list-disc marker:text-indigo-500">
                <li><code class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold">{{ '{%' }} block title {{ '%}' }}</code>: Updates the browser page title. Defaults smoothly to system metadata arrays.</li>
                <li><code class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold">{{ '{%' }} block description {{ '%}' }}</code>: Safely populates and HTML-escapes search engine indexing tags.</li>
                <li><code class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold">{{ '{%' }} block styles {{ '%}' }}</code>: Contains core framework stylesheets (Tailwind CSS and Montserrat). Overridable to eject default fonts and weights.</li>
                <li><code class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold">{{ '{%' }} block head_extensions {{ '%}' }}</code>: Appends custom conditional headers, third-party CDNs, or unique styling rules early in document parsing.</li>
                <li><code class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold">{{ '{%' }} block body_class {{ '%}' }}</code>: Injects structural or state utility classes (e.g., <code>is-dashboard</code>) straight to the <code>&lt;body&gt;</code> element.</li>
                <li><code class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold">{{ '{%' }} block content {{ '%}' }}</code>: Primary application rendering slot. Accepts unique page views inside custom elements.</li>
                <li><code class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold">{{ '{%' }} block scripts {{ '%}' }}</code>: Fires script tags at the very base of the page, directly following framework modal engines and light/dark theme managers.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <hr class="border-slate-800">

        <section class="space-y-4">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white tracking-tight">Step-by-Step Extension Example</h2>
            <p class="text-slate-300">
                To build custom page templates, create a file within your workspace application layout theme and utilize an explicit path namespace fallback pointing to the core skeleton framework. Here is a clean example:
            </p>

            <div class="space-y-2">
                <span class="text-xs font-semibold tracking-wider text-slate-400 uppercase block">Example File Path:</span>
                <div class="bg-slate-950 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg text-xs font-mono text-emerald-400 border border-slate-800">
                    my-awesome-app/views/themes/default/profile/show.twig
                </div>
            </div>

            <pre><code class="language-twig">{{ '{%' }} extends "@core/layouts/main.twig" {{ '%}' }}

{{ '{%' }} block title {{ '%}' }}User Profile - {{ '{{ profile.name }}' }}{{ '{%' }} endblock {{ '%}' }}

{{ '{%' }} block body_class {{ '%}' }}profile-dashboard-layout custom-bg-pattern{{ '{%' }} endblock {{ '%}' }}

{{ '{%' }} block content {{ '%}' }}
    &lt;div class="p-6 bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 rounded-xl shadow"&gt;
        &lt;h1 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white"&gt;Welcome back, {{ '{{ profile.name }}' }}!&lt;/h1&gt;
        &lt;p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-1"&gt;Manage your account parameters below.&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
{{ '{%' }} endblock {{ '%}' }}

{{ '{%' }} block scripts {{ '%}' }}
    &lt;script src="{{ '{{ base_url }}' }}/public/js/profile-validator.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
{{ '{%' }} endblock {{ '%}' }}</code></pre>
        </section>

        <hr class="border-slate-800">

        <section class="space-y-4">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white tracking-tight">Opting Out of Framework Styles</h2>
            <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
                Rhapsody values design flexibility and remains completely unopinionated about your front-end utility choices. If you wish to build custom styles that reject utility frameworks entirely (such as using Bootstrap, custom Sass layers, or clean vanilla CSS structures), you don't need to change any core framework package vendor source files.
            </p>
            <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
                Simply declare an empty or custom-mapped <code class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold">{{ '{%' }} block styles {{ '%}' }}</code> container inside your child workspace template file. This intercepts the asset compilation stage, stripping out Tailwind CSS and Google Fonts, allowing you to establish a fresh stylesheet context from scratch:
            </p>

            <pre><code class="language-twig">{{ '{%' }} extends "@core/layouts/main.twig" {{ '%}' }}

{# --- BYPASS DEFAULT TAILWIND STYLING STACK --- #}
{{ '{%' }} block styles {{ '%}' }}
    &lt;!-- Load Bootstrap or a completely alternative asset pipeline instead --&gt;
    &lt;link href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/bootstrap@5.3.0/dist/css/bootstrap.min.css" rel="stylesheet"&gt;
    &lt;link href="{{ '{{ base_url }}' }}/public/themes/custom/legacy-app.css" rel="stylesheet"&gt;
{{ '{%' }} endblock {{ '%}' }}

{{ '{%' }} block body_class {{ '%}' }}container py-5 bootstrap-context{{ '{%' }} endblock {{ '%}' }}

{{ '{%' }} block content {{ '%}' }}
    &lt;div class="card shadow-sm"&gt;
        &lt;div class="card-body"&gt;
            &lt;h3 class="card-title text-primary"&gt;Decoupled Engine Instance&lt;/h3&gt;
            &lt;p class="card-text text-muted"&gt;Tailwind was completely dropped at parsing. Core SEO schemas and scripts remain active.&lt;/p&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/div custody&gt;
{{ '{%' }} endblock {{ '%}' }}</code></pre>

            <div class="p-4 bg-slate-950 border border-indigo-500/20 rounded-xl space-y-1">
                <h4 class="text-xs font-bold text-indigo-400 tracking-wider uppercase">Architectural Note</h4>
                <p class="text-slate-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
                    Even when you override the default <code>styles</code> block, core processes—such as session notification flash messages, dark-mode preference handlers, application version update alerts, and rich structured microdata JSON-LD schemas for search engines—remain fully secure and functional at the root layer.
                </p>
            </div>
        </section>

    </div>
{% endblock %}